 England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fixby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Essex): habitational name, perhaps from Bittesby in Leicestershire. The village was depopulated in 1494 to make way for sheep pastures. The pronunciation of the surname as <i>Bekysby</i> (1459) and <i>Bixby</i> (1539) would have arisen when bearers of the name migrated away from Leicestershire. Alternatively, <i>Bixby</i> might be an altered form of   Bigby   or <b>Bixley</b>, a Suffolk name."],"variants":[{"name":"Bigsby","meanings":["English (Essex): habitational name from a now abandoned settlement. See   Bixby  ."]},{"name":"Bigby","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Lincolnshire named Bigby, from an Old Danish personal name <i>Bekki</i> + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘settlement, farmstead’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Fixby was born about 1238, in Huddersfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas de Fixby, was 22 and her mother, Mrs. Thomas de Fixby, was 23. She married Richard de Thornhill about 1249, in Thornhill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 2 daughters. She died about 1263, at the age of 27."},"et":{"Abt 1238–Abt 1263":"umbes 1238–umbes 1263","1238–1263":"1238–1263","1262–Female":"1262–Surnud","1238–1287":"1238–1287","1250–1322":"1250–1322","1262–1349":"1262–1349","1262–Male":"1262–Surnud","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1264–Male":"1264–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1217–Male":"1217–Surnud","1217–Female":"1217–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","Abt 1238":"umbes 1238","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","Abt 1263":"umbes 1263","1217":"1217","1349":"1349","1238":"1238","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","about 1249":"umbes 1249","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1262":"umbes 1262","Huddersfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huddersfield, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1238–Abt 1263":"noin 1238–noin 1263","1238–1263":"1238–1263","1262–Female":"1262–Kuollut","1238–1287":"1238–1287","1250–1322":"1250–1322","1262–1349":"1262–1349","1262–Male":"1262–Kuollut","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1264–Male":"1264–Kuollut","1265–Male":"1265–Kuollut","1217–Male":"1217–Kuollut","1217–Female":"1217–Kuollut","about 1250":"noin 1250","Abt 1238":"noin 1238","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","Abt 1263":"noin 1263","1217":"1217","1349":"1349","1238":"1238","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","about 1249":"noin 1249","1265":"1265","1287":"1287","about 1262":"noin 1262","Huddersfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huddersfield, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta